Bank Churn Prediction

Problem Statement¶

Context¶

Businesses like banks which provide service have to worry about problem of 'Customer Churn' i.e. customers leaving and joining another service provider. It is important to understand which aspects of the service influence a customer's decision in this regard. Management can concentrate efforts on improvement of service, keeping in mind these priorities.

Objective¶

You as a Data scientist with the bank need to build a neural network based classifier that can determine whether a customer will leave the bank or not in the next 6 months.

Data Dictionary¶

  • CustomerId: Unique ID which is assigned to each customer

  • Surname: Last name of the customer

  • CreditScore: It defines the credit history of the customer.

  • Geography: A customer’s location

  • Gender: It defines the Gender of the customer

  • Age: Age of the customer

  • Tenure: Number of years for which the customer has been with the bank

  • NumOfProducts: refers to the number of products that a customer has purchased through the bank.

  • Balance: Account balance

  • HasCrCard: It is a categorical variable which decides whether the customer has credit card or not.

  • EstimatedSalary: Estimated salary

  • isActiveMember: Is is a categorical variable which decides whether the customer is active member of the bank or not ( Active member in the sense, using bank products regularly, making transactions etc )

  • Exited : whether or not the customer left the bank within six month. It can take two values 0=No ( Customer did not leave the bank ) 1=Yes ( Customer left the bank )

Intitial Observations on the DataSet¶

Observations:

  • Data set originally contained 10,000 rows and 14 columns.
  • RowNumber, CustomerID and Surname are idetifier columns and hence we will remove them from analysis
  • Geography and Gender are object columns currently. They along with the columns HasCrCard and IsActiveMember will be converted to categorical columns subsequently
  • Rest of the columns are numerical
  • There are no missing or duplicate values. Since there are no missing values, hence no missing value imputation would be done after splitting the data (that otherwise would be done to avoid data leakage).
  • Most of the numerical columns are ditributed with some / minimal skewness.
  • There are some 'seemingly' wrong values in the 'EstimatedSalary' column because the minimum shows 11.58 dollars where as the mean and median are at ~100k. Therefore we deleted all rows where the estimated salary value was less than 10000 dollars.
  • With the deletion of some erroneous rows of 'Estimated Salary' and other unncecessary columns, now there are 9492 Rows and 9 columns

# Following are utility functions that will be used
# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(5, 3), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots
def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=10)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=10,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage
    # Get the current figure and change its sizes
    fig = plt.gcf()
    fig.set_figwidth(3)
    fig.set_figheight(5)
    plt.tight_layout()

    plt.show()  # show the plot

Observations of Univariate Analysis¶

Observations:

  • Credit Scrore - Normal distribution with minimal skewness
  • Geography - Customers from france represent ~50% of the data. Germany and Spain are ~25% each
  • Gender - ~54% are Male customers
  • Age - Right skewed with mean at ~39 and median at 37
  • Tenure - Mostly uniform distribution ( except at extremes of 0 and 10 years) with mean/median at 5 years
  • Balance - Left skewed with mean at ~76k vs median at ~97k. More than 34% of customers have zero dollar balance in their accounts
  • NumOfProducts - ~50% customer have 1 product, 45% have 2 products
  • HasCrCard - 70.7% customer have creditcard
  • IsActiveMember - 51.5% customer are active members
  • EstimatedSalary - Uniform distribution. There are some 'seemingly' wrong values here because the minimum shows 11.58 dollars and this was fixed in the earlier section
  • Exited - 20.39% customer have exited in the dataset

# Utility functions below - 1. function to plot stacked bar chart ; 2. function to plot distribution of numerical variable vs target variable
def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True,normalize='index')#.sort_values(by=sorter, ascending=False)
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 100)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    fig = plt.gcf()
    fig.set_figwidth(1.5)
    fig.set_figheight(3)
    plt.show()

#===================================
### Function to plot distributions
def distribution_plot_wrt_target(data, predictor, target):

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(8, 5))

    target_uniq = data[target].unique()

    axs[0, 0].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[0]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[0]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 0],
        color="teal",
    )

    axs[0, 1].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[1]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[1]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 1],
        color="orange",
    )

    axs[1, 0].set_title("Boxplot w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1, 0], palette="gist_rainbow")

    axs[1, 1].set_title("Boxplot (without outliers) w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 1],
        showfliers=False,
        palette="gist_rainbow",
    )

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Data Preprocessing¶

We will preprocess the dataset in this section to get it ready for model building. Preprocessing will include:

  • Splitting Train, test and validation datasets
  • We would have done missing value imputation ( post splitting to avoid data leaks) here but since there are no missing values, we will skip this step
  • Dummy variable creation ie use pd.get_dummies
  • Scale the data

Model Building¶

Model Evaluation Criterion¶

The logic for choosing the metric that would be the best metric for this business scenario is as follows:

  • Model can make wrong predictions as in :
    • Model predicts a customer will exit but the customer doesn't exit (ie False Positive)
    • Model predicts a customer to not exit but the customer infact exits (ie False Negative)

Predicting a customer to not exit but infact the customer doest exit is more critical & expensive i.e. it is essencially losing a valuable customer or asset. We will therefore need to reduce False Negatives. Therefore the bank would want 'Recall' to be maximized given greater the Recall higher the chances of minimizing false negatives. Hence, the focus while building the model will be on increasing the metric 'Recall'.

Utility function to get the performance score and confusion matrix scores of a model¶

In [33]:
#Define a function that returns model performance metrics and confusion matrix in a form of two lists.
#We will call this function every time we 'fit' a model, to check for its performance and get its metrics and scores

def Get_model_Performace_metrics_and_confusion_matrix(model,X_df,y_df):
  #1. First,get the performance metrics scores
  y_prediction = model.predict(X_df) #predict 'y' using the X data set to being with ; let y_prediction be =1 for predictions >0.5
  y_prediction = (y_prediction > 0.5)
  acc = accuracy_score(y_df, y_prediction)  # get Accuracy metrics
  recall = recall_score(y_df, y_prediction)  # get Recall metrics
  precision = precision_score(y_df, y_prediction)  # get Precision metricx
  f1 = f1_score(y_df, y_prediction)  # get F1-score

  #2 Second, get the confusion matrix
  cm = confusion_matrix(y_df, y_prediction).flatten(order='C') #  values as [tn, fp, fn, tp];  tn: true negative count, fp: false positive count, fn: false negative count, and tp:true positive count

  return [acc,recall,precision,f1], list(cm) # return the two lists

Neural Network with SGD Optimizer¶

  • Let's start with a baseline model having 2 hidden layers and an output layer.
  • We'll use SGD as the optimizer.
  • We'll set epochs to 10, which means the model will pass over the entire data 10 times

#Initializing the neural network
model_0 = Sequential()
# Adding a hidden layer with 64 neurons and relu as activation function
model_0.add(Dense(64, activation='relu', input_dim = X_train.shape[1]))
# Add another hidden layer
model_0.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))
# Add the output layer with the number of neurons required.
model_0.add(Dense(1, activation = 'sigmoid'))

Now that we are done with the model architecture, we will compile the model.

In the compilation function we will provide the loss function that we want to optimize, the corresponding optimization algorithm, and the evaluation metric that we are interested in for evaluating the model -

  • Since this is a binary classification task, we will be minimizing the binary_crossentropy loss function
  • We will instanciate the sgd optimization algorithm to begin with
  • Also since we want to use RECALL metric we will pass that as the metrics of interest aswell
In [36]:
# define loss function
loss_fuc = 'binary_crossentropy'

#create an instance of the SGD optimizer class and pass it to the compile() method of the Keras model
optimizer_sgd = tf.keras.optimizers.SGD(learning_rate=0.0005)

# Select the relavent metrics of interest
metric_R = keras.metrics.Recall() # select this as our metric of interest as explained above # Other potential metrics: metric = 'accuracy';  metric = keras.metrics.Precision();  metric = keras.metrics.F1Score()

Observations:

  • We see that keeping everything else constant while changing only the optimizer from SGD to ADAM, the recall score has now improved to 0.52#@ in the validation set. Also the False Negative count has improved from 362 to 186
  • However interstingly we see that the loss function has worsened to 0.46 for the validation set ( We see that the loss function shows an inverted bell curve ie it improved in the early stages of the epoch run but worsened subsequently)

Neural Network with Adam Optimizer and Dropout¶

# Clear the session and fix the random number seed
tf.keras.backend.clear_session()
np.random.seed(42)
random.seed(42)
tf.random.set_seed(42)

# Setup the NN archicature - We will add the drop out architecture here along with a few addtional layers
model_2 = Sequential()
model_2.add(Dense(128, activation='relu', input_dim = X_train.shape[1]))  # First hidden layer with 128 neurons and relu activation function
model_2.add(Dropout(0.5))                                     # Switching 20% of neurons off randomly at each iteration to avoid overfitting
model_2.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))                     # Second hidden layer with 64 neurons and relu activation function
model_2.add(Dropout(0.5))                                     # Switching 20% of neurons off randomly at each iteration to avoid overfitting
model_2.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))                     # Third hidden layer with 32 neurons and relu activation function
model_2.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))                   # Output layer

# Define the optimization parameters and compile the model
optimizer_adam = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.0005)
metric_R = keras.metrics.Recall()
loss_fuc = 'binary_crossentropy'
model_2.compile(loss = loss_fuc, optimizer = optimizer_adam, metrics=metric_R)
model_2.summary()

loss_fuc = 'binary_crossentropy'
model_3.compile(loss = loss_fuc, optimizer = optimizer_sgd, metrics=metric_R)

# Clear the session and fix the random number seed
tf.keras.backend.clear_session()

# Setup the NN archicature with no drop out
model_4 = Sequential()
model_4.add(Dense(128, activation='relu', input_dim = X_train.shape[1]))  # First hidden layer with 128 neurons and relu activation function
model_4.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))                     # Second hidden layer with 64 neurons and relu activation function
model_4.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))                     # Third hidden layer with 32 neurons and relu activation function
model_4.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))                   # Output layer

# Define the optimization parameters and compile the model
optimizer_adam = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.0005) # SGD optiizer
metric_R = keras.metrics.Recall()
loss_fuc = 'binary_crossentropy'
model_4.compile(loss = loss_fuc, optimizer = optimizer_adam, metrics=metric_R)
model_4.summary()

# Clear the session and fix the random number seed
tf.keras.backend.clear_session()
np.random.seed(42)
random.seed(42)
tf.random.set_seed(42)

# Setup the NN archicature with no drop out; This time we will use tanh activation ( The relu activation was tried offline on this model architecture but it dod not yield good results)
model_5 = Sequential()

model_5.add(Dense(128, activation='tanh', kernel_initializer='glorot_uniform', input_dim = X_train.shape[1]))  # First hidden layer with 128 neurons and relu activation function
model_5.add(Dropout(0.75))                                     # Switching 75% of neurons off randomly at each iteration to avoid overfitting
model_5.add(BatchNormalization())

model_5.add(Dense(128, activation='tanh',kernel_initializer='glorot_uniform'))                     # Second hidden layer with 128 neurons and relu activation function
model_5.add(Dropout(0.75))                                     # Switching 75% of neurons off randomly at each iteration to avoid overfitting
model_5.add(BatchNormalization())

model_5.add(Dense(128, activation='tanh',kernel_initializer='glorot_uniform'))                     # Third hidden layer with 128 neurons and relu activation function
model_5.add(Dropout(0.75))                                     # Switching 75% of neurons off randomly at each iteration to avoid overfitting
model_5.add(BatchNormalization())

model_5.add(Dense(64, activation='tanh',kernel_initializer='glorot_uniform'))                     # Fourth hidden layer with 64 neurons and relu activation function
model_5.add(BatchNormalization())

model_5.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))                   # Output layer

# Define the optimization parameters and compile the model
optimizer_adam = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.0005) # SGD optiizer
metric_R = keras.metrics.Recall()
loss_fuc = 'binary_crossentropy'
model_5.compile(loss = loss_fuc, optimizer = optimizer_adam, metrics=metric_R)
model_5.summary()

Observations:

  • As we see from the above summary, Model-5 ie NN with SMOTE data, ADAM optimizer, Drop out, Batch Normalization and Xavier initialization with 'tanh' activation function has the best performance-recall score in the validation set (of 0.72).
  • Moreover, while the recall-score of Model-3 is close to Model-5 ie 0.7 vs 0.73, the FN (False negative) percentage of Model-3 is 6.2% compared to FN % of Model-5 which is lower at 5.79%.
  • While the vaidation loss of Model-5 is not amongsts the lowest, it is lower than model-3. We are aware that we are prioritizing recall score over the loss function.
  • Time-taken for model build is also resonable at 205 seconds for Model-5.
  • Therefore we will finalize and shotlist Model-5 for next steps.

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations¶

Following are some of the key insights and recommendations for close review and consideration by the bank:

  • We know that 26% of customers who are 'not active' have exited the bank (vs 14% of customer who are active have exited). Given only 51% customers are active members and a resonably big chunk of 49% customers are inactive the bank needs to create targetted marketing campaigns to engage the customer and keep them active.

  • Age is the highest positively correlated column with the 'Exited' column.median age of customers being higher in exited customers, Customer age spans from 18 to 92 with mean at ~39 and median at 37. The campaign to that extent should target older customers.

  • More than 34% of customers have zero dollar balance in their accounts. The Bank can create campaigns to provide attractive interest rates & other incentives to have customer have higher balances in their accounts.

  • Germany has the highest percentage of exited customers (32%), and Germany represents ~25% of the total customer base. To this extent the marketing campaigns can be targetted towards german population.

  • Given females form relatively higher share of exited customers vs males at 25% vs 16% for males, they should form a higher priority in the campaign design.

  • wrt other parameters, NumOfProducts owned by customers, their Tenure, their CreditScore, them having credit cards (or not) and their Estimated Salary showed no perceivable influence on whether they will exit or not. To that extent the campaign design can deprioritize these parameters.

In all the campaign should prioritize targetting Germany customers who are females and median age is higher than 40 years.

Finally, Model-5 should be deployed on expediated basis and predictions be used to make targetted margeting campaigns to 'risky' customers. The model's performane on the test set is resonable at 66% recall score and 6.8% false negative. The model scores can be further improved by increasing the complexity of the NN architecture based on the processing power (and correspondingly the increased cost) the client wants to invest in. The model prediction-output should be monitored routinely and feature adjustments should made on an on going basis as the banks evolves its business including in managing its customers better based on the insights and recommendations provided above.
